So to get a better graph from this data I decided to analyze it through a tibble, after looking through it it is clear this is a very large data set so it is best to break it up. I did this by filtering the data to contain five European countries. From this I plotted it against that company locations ratings and used the geom_violin function so you can see the full extent of the ratings ie. its highest, lowest and avergae(also indicated by a diamond). This graph is organized easy to read and distinguished we are able to actually determine information that was portrayed through the graph. #Good Graph#

chocolate %>%
  group_by(company_location) %>%
  drop_na(rating) %>%
  summarise(mean_rating= mean(rating,
                             na.rm = FALSE))
## # A tibble: 67 × 2
##    company_location mean_rating
##    <chr>                  <dbl>
##  1 Amsterdam               3.31
##  2 Argentina               3.31
##  3 Australia               3.36
##  4 Austria                 3.26
##  5 Belgium                 3.10
##  6 Bolivia                 3.25
##  7 Brazil                  3.28
##  8 Canada                  3.30
##  9 Chile                   3.75
## 10 Colombia                3.20
## # … with 57 more rows
filter(.data = chocolate,
       company_location %in% c("Amsterdam", "France", "Switxerland", "Norway", "U.K."))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x = company_location,
          y = rating,
          fill = company_location,
          color = company_location)) +
  geom_violin(trim = FALSE)+
  stat_summary(fun = mean, 
               geom = "point", 
               shape = 5, 
               size = 5, 
               color = "blue")+
  labs(x = "Company Location", 
       y = "Chocolate Ratings", #y axis
       title = "Chocolate Ratings of European Countries")+
  theme_light()+ 
  theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 10), 
        plot.title = element_text(size = 20),
        legend.position = "none")

ggsave(here("Week_7","Output","Good Plot.pdf"))
